\begin_layout Standard
Besides customer reviews, another important type of online WOM that is relevant
 to marketing is in the form of online conversations among customers.
 As discussed earlier, we perceive these two types of WOM should be evaluated
 separately.
 One key difference between reviews and online conversations is that conversatio
ns by definition have an interactive and social component, and can happen
 both after and 
\emph on
before
\emph default
 the consumption.
 Online conversations involve customers use online social media platforms
 to communicate and discuss a common topic, such as a firm, a brand, or
 a product.
 Conversations among customers used to be confined within offline small
 social circles.
 Such conversations, however, have become more prevalently online with the
 ascendency of social media platforms.
 For a more focused discussion below, we are especially interested in the
 effectiveness of online interactions on social media platforms such as
 Twitter and Facebook.
 We also consider tweeting, retweeting, forwarding, commenting, and other
 activities on these platforms all fit into the loosely defined 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

online conversations.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To answer the question about how effective online conversation are, it would
 be useful to first consider how firms benefit from online conversations
 among customers.
 Or put it differently, what are firms' objectives if they intend to invest
 resources into managing online conversations.
 Because only after we are clear about the objectives, we can evaluate whether
 online conversations are an effective marketing tool.
 In terms of the objectives of managing online conversations, one of the
 benefits of online conversations is to enhance customer awareness, and
 a second goal is to ultimately generate additional sales.
 In the literature of online conversations, however, there is little research
 on the impact on customer awareness, partially because awareness are fairly
 abstract and difficult to measure in this connect.
 On the other hand, awareness closely intertwines with the volume of conversatio
ns, especially the dynamics of how conversations spread to achieve a larger
 volume.
 Accordingly, we focus the discussion on the spread of conversations below.
 Regarding the other objective, the effect of online conversations on demand
 or sales, we will introduce a few recent studies that pay extra attention
 to the measurement challenges and more carefully rely on exogenous data
 variations to inference the effectiveness of online conversations.
 
\end_layout

